WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.700
 Hello, and welcome to our lecture on computer architecture.

00:00:03.700 --> 00:00:06.440
 Now, to some degree, that might seem like a contradiction in terms,

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:09.760
 because the whole name of the course is computer architecture.

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:12.880
 But we're kind of at the point where we have gotten to

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:14.960
 the level where we've built up

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:17.980
 enough basic stuff to really start talking about computer architecture,

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:20.580
 like what's a central processing unit?

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:22.360
 We know what gates are.

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:23.760
 We're going to start with the gates,

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:25.160
 we're not going to worry about transistors,

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:26.140
 we're not going to worry about tubes,

00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:27.680
 we're not going to worry about slide rules,

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:29.680
 and then we're going to just go from there.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:33.400
 Actually, for me, this phase is a little more comfortable.

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:36.480
 I was never a computer engineer or electrical engineer,

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:39.000
 and I understand transistors.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.160
 So that first half was fun for me to do a bunch of research for you and share with

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:47.160
 you what I thought was important about transistors and tubes, etc.

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:49.500
 But now we're going to start with gates.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:51.240
 What can we do with an AND gate,

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:54.340
 an OR gate, NOT gate, exclusive OR, etc.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:56.480
 First, we're going to learn how to start adding numbers,

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:59.320
 because calculation and multiplication in addition are important.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:01.600
 We're going to learn about full adders and half adders.

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.560
 We have to learn about number representation.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:05.840
 How do computers represent numbers?

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:08.860
 Base 2, base 10, and hexadecimal.

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:12.000
 Then we're going to figure out how we actually store data.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.680
 Using gates to store data,

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:15.840
 we'll learn about latches and flip-flops.

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:20.120
 Once we start getting larger and more complicated circuits,

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:24.480
 we're starting to talk about delay and speed and clock rate and all those things.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:27.720
 Then we'll start thinking about how you build

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:32.040
 a computer that can execute programs, machine code,

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:34.680
 where you write software in zeros and ones.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:39.360
 Then ultimately, we'll take a look at how CPUs are put together,

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:41.960
 the architecture of CPUs.

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:46.120
 We often start with computer architecture to talk about the whole computer,

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:48.800
 like there's things like motherboards.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:51.880
 Let me give you a close-up view of a motherboard.

00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:54.620
 But actually, this really isn't just any old motherboard.

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:57.820
 When I started teaching programming back in 2008,

00:01:57.820 --> 00:02:00.880
 this was the motherboard that I would pass around the class.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:02.840
 This is from a desktop computer.

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:06.560
 It's, I think it's probably like a 300 megahertz computer,

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:08.080
 which is really slow.

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:11.680
 I also passed around the CPU that went to this.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:15.760
 So there's the CPU that went to this particular computer.

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:20.360
 I passed it around the class because I wanted people to feel,

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:23.800
 I wanted them to feel the wires that come out of

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:27.040
 these things to get a sense of this is all very electrical.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:28.360
 I've been talking from the beginning of

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:31.160
 the course to the level of this is all very electrical.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:32.640
 So if you look at the back of this,

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:34.320
 there are little tiny wires,

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:37.560
 many of them going on like little streets and chips are

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:42.760
 like buildings that are in a neighborhood and the wires go between them.

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:46.120
 The other thing I wanted people to do is pass this around,

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:48.400
 because you can't feel it here,

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.900
 but these are pointy little things where

00:02:50.900 --> 00:02:53.500
 the chips and connectors come through the board,

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:55.120
 and they're soldered together and that's where

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:58.960
 these connectors are connecting to these wires.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:04.160
 So I just wanted people to get a sense that inside of a computer,

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:07.120
 there was something, and it was physical,

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:11.040
 and it was a thing like a CPU.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:13.280
 The CPU has little pins on it,

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:14.960
 and I wanted people to touch the pins.

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:17.960
 You can see many people over the years have touched these pins,

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:20.040
 and they're all bent up.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:23.960
 So here, I used to pass around this memory chip, and again,

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:28.240
 this is all from 2008 so that people could get

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:34.440
 a physical feeling of what was inside of computers doing all of this work.

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.280
 So generally, if you think about all those wires,

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:40.640
 they generally are taking a zero or a one back and forth,

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:42.920
 and that's what we like about gates,

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.680
 and gates simplify the analogness of

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:51.040
 all circuits and make it so that we can think of them digitally.

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:56.760
 So this is a slide from a lecture that I created in 2008,

00:03:56.760 --> 00:03:59.560
 where I basically said this is what a computer does.

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:03.300
 It has a central processing unit which processes instructions.

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:04.560
 It has main memory,

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:06.980
 which is where the instructions and data are stored.

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:09.520
 It has secondary memory,

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.160
 which is like disk drives where you save files and load data, etc.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.640
 Databases live on disk drives and then put output devices

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:21.560
 like keyboards and mice and things like that.

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:24.800
 So the definitions that I used back then were,

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:26.920
 a central processing unit runs the program,

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:31.320
 the CPU is programmed physically to wonder what to do next.

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:33.040
 It's not really smart,

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:37.080
 but it is very, very fast and we program it to be smart.

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:40.440
 Input devices like keyboard, mouse, and touchscreen.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:43.000
 Output devices like the screen, speakers, printer,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.020
 DVD burner, or whatever.

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:46.760
 Main memory is small, fast,

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:49.800
 temporary storage and secondary memory is the larger,

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:53.720
 more permanent storage that you can power cycle and not come off.

00:04:53.720 --> 00:05:00.240
 So this notion that central processing units are built to think about what next,

00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:02.300
 means that we are inside the computer.

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:03.760
 When we write software,

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:06.000
 we live in the main memory of the computer and

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.800
 our instructions feed the what next, the CPU.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:10.920
 We'll see toward the end,

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:12.760
 we'll understand what the fetch execute cycle,

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.840
 which is fetch, what is it I'm supposed to do next?

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:17.800
 I did that and I'll grab the next one.

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:19.720
 That's the fetch execute cycle.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:22.880
 Now we can program this in something like say Python,

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:24.140
 but really it's not.

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:26.600
 It's really programmed in machine language,

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:27.840
 which is zeros and ones.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:31.200
 By the end of this lecture and the beginning of the next lecture,

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:33.480
 you will be programming in zeros and ones.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.960
 Believe me, this one is a little difficult,

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:42.280
 so you just take your time and follow along with how this goes.

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:44.420
 So from the last lecture,

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:47.640
 we really saw the growth of transistors where we had

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:50.860
 16 transistors on a little tiny circuit to

00:05:50.860 --> 00:05:55.920
 laying out hundreds and millions and billions of transistors on little tiny chips.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:06:00.820
 So with that, we can create increasingly complicated processes.

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:03.160
 Now the way this design process usually works,

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:07.080
 and we did VLSI layout in the previous lectures,

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:11.320
 we tend not to do VLSI layout for modern computers.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:16.780
 We tend to build reusable components like an adder or a latch or something like that,

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:18.800
 and then we wire those all together,

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:23.280
 and then software takes our abstract design of gates and latches

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:25.580
 that think in terms of zeros and ones,

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:30.200
 and components like adders and multipliers and ripple carry adders, etc.,

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.480
 and then turn that into a transistor layout.

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:37.100
 Some of the things that CPUs do are so important,

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:41.720
 like adding and multiplying and little caches and registers,

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:45.920
 that we might tune the hardware layout in the transistors a little bit,

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:49.040
 but in general, software does all of the work and takes

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:52.920
 our abstract design and turns it into an optimal layout for our chip.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:56.160
 Then of course, we use photolithography.

00:06:56.160 --> 00:07:01.400
 So up next, we're going to talk about how we use gates to add numbers.

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:04.640
 Again, going to the point where we have gates,

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:08.860
 now how can we construct multiple gate circuits that

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:12.320
 accomplish the kinds of things that microprocessors want to do.

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:23.960
 [MUSIC]

